==English==
===Etymology===
The origin of the word is uncertain. It is first recorded in the early sixteenth century, and is found almost entirely in Scottish use for a long time. 

There are two schools of thought on the origin. One is your suggestion: that it derives from an assumed Middle English form elf-riche 'elf-land; fairyland', from elf and riche, a Middle English word meaning 'kingdom; land' (related to the usual rich 'having abundant wealth'). Semantically, eldritch would mean 'characteristic of elfs or fairies; supernatural; (hence) eerie, etc.'. 

The other suggestion is that the first element is el- an Old English root meaning 'foreign; strange' (related to else), with the second element the same as discussed above. The semantic sense would thus be 'characteristic of a strange, unknown land'. This suggestion is slightly better phonologically, since we don't have to explain away the -f- from elf.

